<ns0:entry xmlns:ns0="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:ns1="http://schemas.google.com/g/2005" xmlns:ns2="http://schemas.google.com/projecthosting/issues/2009" ns1:etag="W/&quot;CkcMRX47eCl7ImA9WhNSEUQ.&quot;">
		<ns0:id>http://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/full/2662</ns0:id><ns0:author>
			<ns0:name>kschi...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/108470876877739532758/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">We need a way to convince ourselves that the arm validator recognizes what is expected.

&lt;b&gt;- Where are we today?&lt;/b&gt;
Except for a couple dozen (specific) arm instructions (which correspond to validator issues), there is no actual tests for expected behaviour of the instruction decoder.

&lt;b&gt;- Why is this a problem?&lt;/b&gt;
As discovered when looking at the thumb2 decoder, it is very easy to make mistakes in the specification, and such errors will never be detected unless one is very lucky.

&lt;b&gt;- The proposed enhancement:&lt;/b&gt;
Write a decoder testing tool that will allow one to specify an ARM instruction, and expected cases where it should fail, such that we enumerate a reasonable representation of possible encodings of that instruction. These enumerations should result in the corresponding (expected) decoder being matched.

&lt;b&gt;- Exit criteria:&lt;/b&gt;
When we feel safe enough with the level of testing.

&lt;b&gt;- Anticipated impact:&lt;/b&gt;
Unit testing of the decoder that will pick up unexpected changes in the automatically generated decoder.
